Difference between for loop and enhanced for loop (for-each) in Java:

1. Traditional for Loop

Syntax:
for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    System.out.println(arr[i]);
}

Key Points:
a) Uses index (i)
b) Full control over loop:
      i) Forward / backward
     ii) Skip elements (i += 2)
c) Can modify elements
d) Works with arrays and collections


2. Enhanced for Loop (for-each loop)

Syntax:
for (int num : arr) {
    System.out.println(num);
}

Key Points:
a) No index, directly accesses elements
b) Cleaner and more readable
c) Internally uses iterator
d) Mainly for read-only traversal

Differences in both:

Feature              Traditional for Loop              Enhanced for Loop
Syntax complexity	            More	                          Simple
Index access	                Yes	                              No
Modify elements	              Yes	                        No (only copy)
Reverse iteration	            Yes	                              No
Step control (i+=2)	          Yes	                              No
Readability	                Moderate	                         High
Best use case	            Complex logic	                 Simple traversal


Important Example: 

Enhanced loop cannot modify original array:
for (int num : arr) {
    num = num * 2; // Won’t update original array
}

Traditional loop can modify original array:
for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    arr[i] = arr[i] * 2;
}


When to Use What:
i) Use enhanced for loop → when you only need to read data
ii) Use for loop → when you need index or modification
